description.narrative:
AJMTEM has developed its first ever strategic plan (Strategic Plan of AJMTEM 2020-2023) and an accompanying RAF.
 
Starting in November 2019, the strategic planning process was part of the activities supported under the pre-core support grant. The final version of the Strategic Plan was approved by the General Assembly at its meeting in late February 2020. At the meeting, the General Assembly agreed that the Strategic Plan could be further improved based on the recommendations of this follow-up SBA, and that the changes could be confirmed by Board decision only.
As further elaborated on in Chapter 4, the Strategic Plan and RAF were developed in a participatory manner in consultation with staff members and the Board, and with the support of an external consultant.
The 20-page Strategic Plan includes (but is not limited to):
Vision and mission statements as well as a list of core values (and a description of how these are promoted);
An analysis of the political, economic, social, technological, legal and environmental context (PESTLE analysis);
An analysis of strengths, weaknesses, opportunities and threats (SWOT analysis);
A vision statement for the organisation (internal vision) and a description of its strategic niche and what action will be taken to promote organisational and financial sustainability;
An organisational chart visualising the desired future structure of the organisation;
A section listing target groups and strategic objectives for the period 2020-2023; A code of ethics, communication policy, and anti-corruption policy;
Principles for promoting gender equality and non-discrimination as well as environmental protection, and;
A monitoring and evaluation framework and risk analysis.
 
Overall, the Strategic Plan is a comprehensive document. In line with priority recommendation 1, it can be said to clearly describe the identity of the organisation. 
The Strategic Plan identifies some risks and risk management actions it is not done in the manner recommended by the SBA. A comprehensive risk assessment framework normally includes, as one element, a risk matrix presenting (a) different categories of risks, (b) a rating/evaluation of each risk (in terms of impact and probability), (c) risk mitigation actions with timelines for implementation, and, (d) information on who is responsible for each risk mitigation action. It is noted that AJMTEM’s new Operational Manual has a section on risk management that defines categories of risks and includes a risk management flowchart and model action plan for risk management. Risks are also identified in the RAF (see below). AJMTEM will further develop the risk assessment document in the inicipient phace of the core support.
The RAF has columns presenting results, indicators, reference indicators, aims, frequency of monitoring, verification methods, M&E methods, and risks. The results include one impact statement, three outcomes statements, and a number of outputs for each outcome. In general, the RAF has been updated after the submittion of the follow-up report and now it fully complies with established RBM principles.
